Canadian leftists during a time when it was uncommon for disabled men to lead. They examine Kingsley’s endeavours for justice against the Northern Pacific Railway, and how Kingsley’s life intersected with immigration law and free-speech rights. Able to Lead brings a turbulent period in North American history to life, highlighting Kingsley’s profound legacy for the twenty-first-century political left.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmputeeszCanadavBiography. 0aAmputeeszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPoliticianszCanadavBiography. 0aPoliticianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSocialistszCanadavBiography. 0aSocialistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh1 aIsitt, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486578440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865784/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles